A Pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic Model for the Quantitative Prediction of Dofetilide Clinical QT Prolongation from Human Ether-a-go-go-related Gene Current Inhibition Data

Daniël M. Jonker PhD, 
Division of Pharmacokinetics and Drug Therapy, Faculty of Pharmacy, Uppsala University, PO Box 591, 75124 Uppsala, Sweden E-mail:
Leslie A. Kenna PhD, 
Derek Leishman PhD,

First published: 09 June 2005
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.clpt.2005.02.004
Citations: 73

Abstract

Background

QT prolongation is an important biomarker of the arrhythmia torsades de pointes and appears to be related mainly to blockade of delayed inward cardiac rectifier potassium currents. The aim of this study was to quantify the relationship between in vitro human ether-a-go-go-related gene (hERG) potassium channel blockade and the magnitude of QT prolongation in humans for the class III antiarrhythmic dofetilide.

Methods

The in vitro affinity and activity of dofetilide were determined in recombinant cell cultures expressing the hERG channel, and the QT-prolonging effect of dofetilide was assessed in 5 clinical studies (80 healthy volunteers and 17 patients with ischemic heart disease). A population pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic analysis of the in vitro and in vivo data was performed in NONMEM by use of the operational model of pharmacologic agonism to estimate the efficiency of transduction from ion channel binding to Fridericia-corrected QT response.

Results

A 3-compartment pharmacokinetic model with first-order absorption characterized the time course of dofetilide concentrations. On the basis of an in vitro potency of 5.13 ng/mL for potassium current inhibition and predicted unbound dofetilide concentrations, the estimated transducer ratio (τ) of 6.2 suggests that the QT response plateaus before currents are fully blocked. In our study population, 10% hERG blockade corresponds to a QT prolongation of 20 ms (95% confidence interval, 12–32 ms). With long-term dofetilide administration, tolerance develops with a half-life of 4.7 days.

Conclusions

The current mechanism-based pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic model quantified the relationship between in vitro hERG channel blockade and clinical QT prolongation for dofetilide. This model may prove valuable for assessing the risk of QT prolongation in humans for other drugs that selectively block the hERG channel on the basis of in vitro assays and pharmacokinetic properties.

Clinical Pharmacology & Therapeutics (2005) 77, 572–582; doi: 10.1016/j.clpt.2005.02.004

Torsades de pointes is a life-threatening form of ventricular tachycardia that is a documented side effect of more than 40 nonantiarrhythmic drugs,1 resulting in concerns about the safety of at least 100 drugs across all therapeutic drug classes.1,2,3 The majority of drugs that promote torsades de pointes inhibit the rapidly activating delayed rectifier potassium current (IKr) channels in cardiac cells and cause a measurable prolongation of the QT interval on the surface electrocardiogram (ECG). In clinical safety studies, cardiac repolarization is monitored principally by the QT interval. In preclinical studies, on the other hand, the human ether-a-go-go-related gene (hERG) assay is widely used as a model for the effect of compounds on IKr conduction.

As a general safety guideline for the interpretation of such studies, a provisional 30-fold safety margin between the maximally reached free plasma concentration and the in vitro 50% inhibitory concentration (IC50) for IKr inhibition is currently proposed.2,4 Although useful as a screening method, this safety margin does not allow one to quantitatively predict the actual level of QT prolongation expected in vivo. In addition, the safety margin does not account for the interindividual variability in pharmacokinetics and the variability in drug sensitivity.5 Thus the magnitude of this margin may be dictated by only a few drugs and is likely to be larger than necessary for most drugs. Although both IKr inhibition properties in vitro and QT-prolonging effects in vivo have been characterized for many drugs, the quantitative relationship between these 2 outcomes remains uncertain. One reason is that it is common for drugs to act on multiple cardiac ion channels involved in repolarization. Depending on the magnitude of the effect on all channels together, this can either decrease or increase the degree of QT prolongation that would result from IKr inhibition alone.2,6,7 Dofetilide selectively inhibits IKr with little or no effect on other cardiac ion channels8,9,10 or conduction velocity11 and is, therefore, an ideal candidate for quantifying the in vitro-in vivo correlation between IKr inhibition and QT prolongation.

The operational model of pharmacologic agonism offers the opportunity to interpret QT studies on a mechanistic basis.12 This approach establishes a link between receptor binding or ion channel binding and the pharmacologic effect via a parametric description of the signal transduction process. This “system-specific” signal transduction function is driven by receptor binding or ion channel binding (the “drug-specific” part of the model). In this manner, a new parameterization of the concentration-effect relationship is obtained that allows in vivo estimation of the efficiency of signal transduction.13 The operational model of pharmacologic agonism has successfully been applied to quantify the in vivo transduction efficiency of the electroencephalogram effects of γ-aminobutyric acid type A receptor modulators14 and for the antilipolytic effects of adenosine A1 agonists.15 In this study the operational model is used to assess the relationship of IKr inhibition in vitro to the extent of QT prolongation in humans.

METHODS

hERG assay

The activity of dofetilide was determined in recombinant cell cultures expressing the hERG potassium channel. The method for stable transfection of this ion channel has been described elsewhere.16 The hERG currents were studied in a whole-cell configuration at room temperature by use of standard patch-clamp techniques.16 The recordings were performed on cells with access resistances below 20 MΩ and seal resistances greater than 1 GΩ. Dofetilide was dissolved in dimethylsulfoxide (DMSO) and diluted to 0.01, 1.3, 13, and 132 ng/mL with standard external solution. Vehicle DMSO concentrations were constant throughout (0.1%). The concentration dependence of currents measured in the presence of DMSO or dofetilide was assessed.

Binding assay

The dissociation constant of dofetilide was determined in the range 0.14 to 4420 ng/mL (10 concentrations, 5 replications). The methods for this assay have been described in detail elsewhere (patent application WO 03/021271). In brief, membranes were prepared from HEK293 cells stably expressing the hERG potassium channel. The scintillation proximity assay technique was used. Membrane homogenate was precoupled with beads at 4°C for 1.5 hours (Roller SRT1; Stuart Scientific, Redhill in Surrey, United Kingdom). Membrane and bead suspension was incubated in white 96-well plates with 2.21 ng/mL tritium-labeled dofetilide (specific activity, 18 Ci · mmol−1 · L−1) in the absence and presence of test compound. Plates were incubated with shaking for 1 hour at room temperature; beads were then allowed to settle for 30 minutes before counting. Nonspecific binding was determined in the presence of 4.4 ×103 ng/mL dofetilide and subtracted from the total binding to obtain the specific binding, which was subsequently used in the data analysis.

Clinical studies

The clinical data for this analysis were collected in 5 phase I studies that were performed from 1988 to 1992. They included 80 healthy volunteers and 17 patients with ischemic heart disease administered dofetilide by the oral or intravenous route. In each study, repeated measures of dofetilide plasma concentrations and QT interval were taken for pharmacokinetic (PK)–pharmacodynamic (PD) evaluation. The data set contained 4768 measurements of dofetilide plasma concentrations and 11,828 QT observations. Demographic information including age, weight, height, and sex was recorded, and standard biochemistry tests for liver function (AST, ALT, and serum alkaline phosphatase) and kidney function (serum creatinine) were performed. Ethics committee approval was obtained for each study, and each study participant provided written consent.

Separate analyses of 4 of the 5 studies have been published previously.17,18,19 The various study designs and the characteristics of the study participants are shown in Table I. In studies A, B, and D, dofetilide was administered in single doses with a 7-day washout period between study occasions. In studies C and E, dofetilide was administered 2 or 3 times daily over periods of 5 and 24 days. In study E, dofetilide was administered 2 times daily versus once every 5 days as described elsewhere.18

Venous blood samples were collected and analyzed by an automated double-antibody radioimmunoassay.20 The lower limit of quantification was 0.05 ng/mL. In study E, recordings were made of 3-lead ECGs, and in all other studies, 12-lead ECGs were recorded. Measurements of intervals for QT, RR (time in milliseconds between 2 successive R waves), and HR (heart rate in beats per minute) were obtained from electronically recorded ECGs by use of a validated computer program with operator oversight. The collected QT values were corrected for RR or HR with Fridericia's formula, as follows: QTCF = QT · (1000/RR)1/3 = QT · (HR/60)1/3. In all studies, subjects with resting rate-corrected QT interval greater than or equal to 420 ms were excluded from study participation.

PK-PD data analysis

The analysis was performed in NONMEM, version VIβ (GloboMax), by use of the first-order conditional estimation method (FOCE) with interaction. On the basis of the final PK model, individual estimates of dofetilide concentrations were generated at QT observation times and used in a 2-stage approach for development of the PD model. This approach is computationally much faster than simultaneous estimation of the PK and PD models and is not expected to compromise precision and accuracy of the parameter estimates unless the PK model is misspecified.21 The final models were rerun in NONMEM, version V, to ensure consistency of the results with the commercially available release of NONMEM.

The model-building process was guided by graphic analysis in Xpose, version 3.1,22 and changes in the objective function value (OFV) were obtained from NONMEM. The difference in OFV between 2 nested models is approximately χ2-distributed and can be used for hypothesis testing. A difference at the 5% significance level was required for the addition of a model parameter. The uncertainty in model parameters is reported as the relative standard error (rSE) in the parameter and variance estimates obtained from NONMEM.

PK model

Linear compartment models with elimination from the central (blood) compartment were considered to describe the disposition of dofetilide. The potential influence of covariates such as creatinine clearance on the structural PK parameter estimates was assessed within NONMEM. The semiautomated stepwise procedure that was used for covariate selection has been described in detail elsewhere.23 A total of 25 parameter-covariate relationships were tested and selected on the basis of a model improvement at the 5% significance level in the forward (building) step of the procedure and at the 1% significance level in the backward (reducing) step.

PD model

On the basis of the final PK model, a data set was constructed containing predicted dofetilide concentrations for an individual at the time points corresponding to QTCF observations. The predicted dofetilide concentrations were transformed into unbound dofetilide concentrations by multiplication with the unbound fraction of dofetilide, which was fixed to the value of 0.36.24 On the basis of the unbound dofetilide concentrations, the affinity and activity of dofetilide in vitro were related to the QT effects in humans through the use of the operational model of pharmacologic agonism. The simultaneous analysis of the in vitro data and the clinical data permitted estimation of the efficiency of transduction of hERG inhibition into the observed QT effect. This was achieved by use of the following function to relate the observed QTCF values to the unbound dofetilide concentration:
(4)
in which QT0 is the average QTCF value in each subject at baseline, QTm is the maximum QT prolongation that is possible in the system relative to baseline, τ is the transducer ratio, and n represents a slope factor to account for stimulus amplification in the process of signal transduction. The transducer ratio τ equals the ratio of the maximum current inhibition Imax to the fraction of inhibited potassium channels corresponding to the half-maximum response. This dimensionless parameter may assume values greater than 0 and is governed by the efficiency of signal transduction (high values corresponding to high efficiency). The parameters of the operational model (equation 4) can be transformed into the parameters of the sigmoid Emax model as follows:
(5)
(6)
in which Emax is the maximally observed QT response relative to baseline and EC50 is the dofetilide concentration corresponding to a half-maximum QT response. For relating the QT response to dofetilide binding instead of current inhibition, KI was replaced with KA in equation 4, thereby defining τ as the ratio of the bound dofetilide concentration CB to the concentration of bound potassium channels corresponding to the half-maximum response.

The residual variability in QT0 in each individual was assumed to be equal to the intraindividual variability during dofetilide treatment. This estimate of variability was, therefore, conditional on all QT observations and with a single variance parameter, θadd, which accounted simultaneously for the uncertainty in QT0 and for intraindividual variability. The stepwise procedure that was followed to assess the influence of covariates on the PK parameters was also used to identify covariates for the structural PD model parameters. The potential influence of the covariates disease state (SUBJ), average baseline QT interval, age, and body weight on the structural model parameters τ and QTm was tested. On the basis of the PD parameter estimates in the final model, a 95% confidence interval for the predicted QT-interval prolongation in the typical individual was constructed. Observations were simulated in 1000 individuals from the variance in the estimates of KI, QT0, τ, and QTm obtained from the variance-covariance matrix provided by NONMEM. From these simulated QT observations, the 95% confidence interval was determined by ranking the simulated data and excluding the 2.5 percentiles. A 95% prediction interval for the population was constructed by simulating 1000 individuals from the interindividual variability in KI, QT0, τ, and QTm and the intraindividual variability. In the case that less than 95% of the observations are found within this interval, the model is likely to be misspecified.

Study dependence

The stability of the parameter estimates in the final population PK-PD models was assessed by re-estimation of the models with 1 study at a time removed from the data.25

RESULTS

In vitro assays

The binding curve of dofetilide and the inactivation of hERG currents are shown in Fig 1. The dissociation constant KA of dofetilide was estimated to be 4.79 ng/mL (rSE, 6%), and the residual error was 0.195 (rSE, 15%). The estimated value of KA was very similar to the estimate of KI for inhibition of potassium currents by dofetilide, which was 5.13 ng/mL (rSE, 15%), with 42% variability between cells (rSE, 53%). The baseline current relative to vehicle was estimated to be 0.969 (rSE, 11%), with 31% variability between cells (rSE, 27%). The residual error was estimated to be 0.08 (rSE, 13%).

PK analysis

A 3-compartment model with first-order absorption and a lag time was found to appropriately characterize the disposition of dofetilide. Interindividual variability could be characterized by use of exponential models for the parameters indicated in Table I. Four linear parameter-covariate relationships were identified as follows: a decrease in clearance with age (ΔOFV, −39.7, on addition of the covariate), an increase in total peripheral volume with body weight (ΔOFV, −15.3), an increase in clearance with body weight (ΔOFV, −14.2), and a decrease in peripheral volume with serum albumin concentration (ΔOFV, −7.6).

However, for estimating uncertainty in the model parameters, the covariate model had to be simplified by exclusion of the relationship of peripheral volume to serum albumin, which was the least significant covariate relationship. The parameter estimates obtained with this final PK model are listed in Table II. When these values are compared with those obtained with the basic PK model without covariates, the covariates explained very little of the variability in the parameter values. The covariate model would, therefore, not have value for the prediction of dofetilide concentrations, although the fit to the observed data was improved to a statistically significant extent. Some diagnostic plots for the final model are shown in the left panel of Fig 2 and did not reveal trends in the predictions versus the observations or in the predictions versus the time after the first dose.

PD analysis

The structure of the final PD model is schematically depicted in Fig 3. The operational model of pharmacologic agonism with an effect compartment and a feedback compartment appropriately characterized the QT effect. The average baseline QT interval was calculated from observations at predicted dofetilide concentrations lower than 5 × 10−4 ng/mL and was found at 386.2 ms (rSE, 18%). The estimates of the structural model parameters are listed in Table III. On the basis of the estimates of QTm and τ, the corresponding parameter values in the sigmoid Emax model were 105 ms for Emax and 0.98 ng/mL for EC50. The potency in vivo was 5.2-fold higher than the potency estimated in the hERG assay. This difference is depicted in Fig 4 and implies that dofetilide binding is not saturated at concentrations where the QT effect approaches a maximum.

An effect compartment was added to the model to describe a delay between the appearance of dofetilide in serum and the QT effect. On the basis of the first-order rate constant ke0, the half-life for the rate of diffusion from the blood to the heart cells was 12 minutes. A gradual decrease in the QT response over time was noted on graphic examination of the data from studies B and E. This decrease was accounted for by the addition of a feedback compartment that was initially empty and filled at a rate that was governed by the observed QT effect according to a first-order rate constant (ktol):
(7)

The “amount” M in the feedback compartment negatively affected the transducer ratio τ as shown in Fig 3. In Fig 3, τ0 represents the unaffected transducer ratio and KM is a parameter determining the extent of tolerance development. On the basis of the estimate of ktol (Table III), the half-life for tolerance development was 4.7 days. This model described the development of tolerance significantly better than the same model affecting QTm.

During stepwise covariate selection, a linear increase of τ with QT0 (ΔOFV, −22.4, on addition of the covariate) and a linear increase of τ with age (ΔOFV, −5.8) were detected. Of these relationships, only the effect of QT0 on τ was significant in the backward search. Some diagnostic plots for the final model are shown in Fig 2 and did not reveal any substantial trends. Because the estimates for dofetilide potency were very similar in the binding assay and in the hERG assay (4.79 ng/mL versus 5.13 ng/mL), the parameter estimates based on the hERG assay were not substantially different from the values reported in Table III (data not shown).

The final PD model yielded the relationship between relative block of hERG current and QT-interval prolongation (Fig 5). This graph allows determination of the extent of QT-interval prolongation that is expected given a certain degree of hERG blockade. On the basis of the present analysis with dofetilide, the inset in Fig 5 shows that 20 ms of QT-interval prolongation is exceeded with statistical significance at 13% blockade of hERG currents. This value is 7% for a QT-interval prolongation of 5 ms. The width of the confidence interval depends on the precision of both the clinical studies and the in vitro assay. Predictions from the dofetilide binding study instead of the current inhibition assay were not significantly different from the prediction that is shown in Fig 5, but the confidence interval was slightly more narrow (data not shown).

Study dependence

The final PK and PD models were challenged by omitting 1 study at a time from the model. The influence of any study on the parameter estimates was less than 20% for all parameters but Q1 in the PK model and ke0 in the PD model. These parameter values were strongly dependent on the inclusion of study A, which is not surprising, given that this study contained the greater part of the intravenous dofetilide administrations. The estimates of the tolerance parameters ktol and KM were dependent on the inclusion of study B and, to a lesser extent, on the inclusion of study E (ie, the only studies with repeated oral dosing). The finding that the named PK and PD parameters were more than 20% different for certain studies was, therefore, not regarded as a problem with the model.

DISCUSSION

The objective of this analysis was to relate the magnitude of dofetilide's action at the hERG potassium channel in vitro to QT prolongation in humans. This was achieved by application of the operational model of pharmacologic agonism, yielding an estimated value of the transducer ratio τ of 6.2. This estimate corresponds to a 5-fold increase in potency after signal transduction and is in line with the observation that 10% to 20% inhibition of hERG currents in vitro reflects clinically significant QT prolongation and torsades de pointes more accurately than do IC50 values.26,27 According to our results, 10% inhibition of hERG currents by dofetilide corresponds to 20 ms of QT-interval prolongation (95% confidence interval, 12–32 ms).

The current Food and Drug Administration draft guidance suggests that an increased risk for torsades de pointes exists at 20 ms of QT-interval prolongation or more.28 Thus, in the population studied here, the observation of less than 5% hERG blockade by dofetilide may be interpreted as indicative of safeness with respect to torsades de pointes whereas 5% to 10% hERG blockade corresponds to a QT-interval prolongation of 5 to 20 ms and is inconclusive. The current model allows calculation, from any degree of hERG blockade, of the probability that the QT interval will be prolonged above a threshold value of interest. This may be useful for assessing the proarrhythmic risk relative to the expected therapeutic benefit, especially for drug candidates that are being developed for the treatment of a serious condition.

Extrapolation of these results to compounds other than dofetilide must, however, be performed with caution because no prediction can provide a guarantee for drug safety or proof with regard to drug toxicity. Although compounds that are relatively selective for the hERG K+ channel block this channel at concentrations that are generally close to the free plasma concentrations found in clinical use, this is generally not the case for compounds with mixed ion channel activity.10 Consequently, it is not possible to reliably predict the extent of QT prolongation for compounds that affect cardiac repolarization through ionic currents other than IKr. Examples exist of compounds that show false-positive results for an increased risk of torsades de pointes in the hERG assay (eg, verapamil and ketoconazole) and of compounds that show false-negative results (eg, nifedipine).10 We are at present evaluating a number of QT-prolonging agents using the operational modeling approach with the aim to obtain insight into the magnitude of prediction errors with selectively acting compounds versus drugs with mixed ion channel activity. The evaluation of multiple compounds with the operational modeling approach allows estimation of the hERG IC50 value in vivo.13,14 By comparing these estimates with estimates obtained in vitro, it is possible to identify any systematic error introduced by the in vitro study conditions. Such a systematic error does not affect predictions for dofetilide but could bias predictions for other compounds based on this model.

Caution should also be taken when these results are extrapolated to compounds that will be used by patient populations that are different from our study population, which included mostly healthy male volunteers. Female sex, congestive heart failure, baseline long QT interval, and hypokalemia are among the risk factors for torsades de pointes.7,29 The finding that the parameter τ increased significantly with the baseline QT interval length corresponds to an increased potency of dofetilide and is in line with the association of long baseline QT intervals to an increased risk for torsades de pointes. In contrast, no difference was found in any of the PD parameters between healthy volunteers and patients with congestive heart failure, even though congestive heart failure is a known risk factor for torsades de pointes. The failure to detect such a difference may be a result of the relatively small number of patients in the analyzed studies. For the same reason, it was not possible to detect differences in the QT response related to sex in our study population.

The current analysis of several studies simultaneously allowed the development of a PK-PD model for dofetilide that is more detailed than previously published models for the drug. The final PK estimates were in good agreement with the corresponding values estimated elsewhere.24,30,31 The current model supported estimation of a sigmoidally shaped concentration-QT relationship, which is a more physiologically relevant model compared with previously published linear PD models for dofetilide.17,18,30 A sigmoidal Emax model was used to describe QT-interval prolongation by dofetilide in 1 previously published report and resulted in estimates of Emax and EC50 that were similar in comparison with our results.31

Age and body weight were found to influence clearance and body weight peripheral volume in the PK model. A relationship between clearance and creatinine clearance (CLCR) was not found, which is surprising because the total clearance of dofetilide has been shown to be proportional to CLCR.32 Moreover, dose adjustment on the basis of CLCR was reported to considerably reduce the incidence of torsades de points in patients with chronic heart failure.33 The failure to detect a clearance-CLCR relationship in the current analysis is likely to be a result of the relatively small number of patients with poor renal function.

The QT-prolonging effects of dofetilide exhibit reverse-rate dependence, meaning that the effect diminishes with increasing heart rate. In this study Fridericia's formula was used to correct the QT observations for heart rate. This formula has been shown to be superior to Bazett's correction34 but may be inferior to individualized correction of QT observations, which is the correction method preferred by many authors at this time. However, in this study the choice of a particular correction method minimally affected the PD parameter estimates, because the dofetilide concentration did not significantly influence heart rate (data on file).

In conclusion, the relationship between hERG channel blockade and QT prolongation in humans was quantified for dofetilide by use of the operational model of pharmacologic agonism. The proposed model is a first step toward predicting the degree and range of QT prolongation in humans for other drugs that selectively block the hERG channel on the basis of in vitro assays and human PK properties. Especially for drugs that are found to block 5% to 10% of hERG channels at relevant concentrations, this model may be a valuable tool for assessing the proarrhythmic risk relative to the expected therapeutic benefit.

We acknowledge Lars Lindbom for sharing the code that was used for study deletion diagnostics.

Drs Leishman, Wallis, and Milligan are employees of Pfizer.
